item.title: Malaysia Closes Investigation Into Prime Minister Najib Razak’s Funds
item.description: The attorney general’s decision appears to prolong the premiership of Mr. Najib, who has struggled to explain the more than $600 million sent to his personal accounts.
item.dc:creator: THOMAS FULLER
item.media:description: Prime Minister Najib Razak of Malaysia leaving Parliament in Kuala Lumpur on Tuesday. Mr. Najib has struggled to explain why more than $600 million was transferred to him.

item.title: Henry Worsley, a British Adventurer Trying to Cross Antarctica, Dies at 55
item.description: Mr. Worsley abandoned his 1,000-mile trek only 30 miles from his goal after suffering from exhaustion and dehydration.
item.dc:creator: BRUCE WEBER
item.media:description: Prince William, left, with the explorer Henry Worsley at Kensington Palace in London in October. Mr. Worsley died after trying to cross the Antarctic alone and without support.

item.title: Libyan Lawmakers Reject U.N.-Backed Unity Government
item.description: The internationally recognized Parliament voted down a proposed 32-member cabinet in a blow to international efforts to help form a unified government.
item.dc:creator: KAREEM FAHIM

item.title: Corsico Journal: Cafeteria Crackdown Prompts Cries of Bean Counting in Italy
item.description: The mayor, seeing that Corsico had a debt of over a million euros in unpaid lunch fees, decided that children whose parents had not paid would not be allowed to eat cafeteria-prepared meals.
item.dc:creator: ELISABETTA POVOLEDO
item.media:credit: Alessandro Grassani for The New York Times
item.media:description: Anita Cimino owes more than 2,000 euros, or $2,160, in lunch bills. She said she was trying to work out a payment plan with the city.

item.title: Open Source: Online, Egypt’s Internet Activists Mourn Their Stifled Revolt
item.description: The anniversary of the Jan. 25 revolution was commemorated quietly by some of those who helped drive millions of Egyptians to the streets in 2011.
item.category: Middle East and North Africa Unrest (2010- )
item.dc:creator: ROBERT MACKEY

item.title: World Briefing: Central African Republic: Court Invalidates Legislative Election
item.description: The Central African Republic’s constitutional court scrapped results from a legislative election, citing irregularities like illegible ballots and poor training for election workers.
item.dc:creator: MARGAUX BENN

item.title: World Briefing: Police Agency Warns of More Terrorist Attacks
item.description: Islamic State extremists will keep trying attacks on so-called soft targets in Europe as the group increasingly goes global.
item.category: Islamic State in Iraq and Syria (ISIS)
item.dc:creator: THE ASSOCIATED PRESS

item.title: Police Presence in Egypt Mutes Most Protests on 5th Anniversary of Uprising
item.description: Egyptians marked the fifth anniversary of the uprising that toppled President Hosni Mubarak with a handful of flash protests but none of the violence or anger that drove the uprising.
item.dc:creator: DECLAN WALSH
item.media:description: The police patrolled in Cairo on Monday, the anniversary of the 2011 uprising that deposed Hosni Mubarak as president.

item.title: El Salvador’s Advice on Zika: Don’t Have Babies
item.description: Grappling with a mosquito-borne virus linked to brain damage in infants, El Salvador is advising all women in the country not to get pregnant until 2018.
item.dc:creator: AZAM AHMED
item.media:description: A health worker fumigated the Altos del Cerro neighborhood in El Salvador last week as part of preventive measures against the Zika virus.

item.title: World Briefing: Taiwan: Scores Die as Cold Descends
item.description: Temperatures abruptly plunged to a 16-year low of 39 degrees Fahrenheit in the subtropical capital.
item.dc:creator: THE ASSOCIATED PRESS

item.title: World Briefing: Yemen: Top Judge and 6 Relatives Are Killed in Airstrike
item.description: Airstrikes by the Saudi-led military coalition hit the home of a senior judge in Sana, killing the judge along with his relatives.
item.dc:creator: SHUAIB ALMOSAWA

item.title: Iran’s Sanctions Lift, and the West Goes to Talk Business
item.description: Airbus orders, likely to be partly financed with loans from European export-credit agencies, could be announced as early as this week, an official said.
item.dc:creator: NICOLA CLARK and CLIFFORD KRAUSS
item.media:description: An Airbus plane from the Iranian private airline Mahan Air in 2015. Iran is looking to place orders for more than 100 European-made aircraft.

item.title: U.N. Envoy for Syria Says Peace Talks Will Begin Friday
item.description: The envoy, Staffan de Mistura, said the talks in Geneva, aimed at a general cease-fire, would be “uphill” and declined to identify who was invited.
item.dc:creator: NICK CUMMING-BRUCE and SOMINI SENGUPTA

item.title: Pope Francis, Catholics and Lutherans Will Recall Reformation
item.description: Pope Francis will participate in a joint worship service in Sweden as part of a series of events to commemorate the 500th anniversary of the Reformation.
item.dc:creator: LAURIE GOODSTEIN

item.title: Iran Still a Leading Executioner of Minors, Report Says
item.description: Amnesty International said Iran had executed 73 juvenile offenders since 2005, despite pledging in 1994 to end the death penalty for those under 18.
item.dc:creator: RICK GLADSTONE

item.title: Cecil Parkinson, British Politician Thwarted by Sex Scandal, Dies at 84
item.description: Mr. Parkinson served in the government of Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher and appeared to be a candidate to succeed her until revelations of an extramarital affair.
item.dc:creator: THE ASSOCIATED PRESS

item.title: Argentina Scrambles to Fight Biggest Plague of Locusts in 60 Years
item.description: Warm, wet winters spawned a locust infestation in dry northern forests. In 10 days, the insects will be mature enough to form flying swarms that devour crops.
item.category: Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations
item.dc:creator: JONATHAN GILBERT
item.media:description: A swarm of locusts in September in the Lavalle area of Santiago del Estero Province, Argentina. Farmers last year reported seeing swarms that were four miles wide and two miles high.

item.title: Strong Earthquake Rattles Spain and Morocco
item.description: The temblor caused some material damage in southern Spain and northern Morocco, although no deaths or injuries were reported.
item.dc:creator: RAPHAEL MINDER

item.title: Two Cases Suggest Zika Virus Could Be Spread Through Sex
item.description: The evidence is slim, but some experts want scientists to investigate whether a virus linked to birth defects and commonly transmitted by mosquitoes could be spread sexually.
item.category: Centers for Disease Control and Prevention
item.dc:creator: DONALD G. McNEIL Jr.
item.media:description: From left: Kevin Kobylinski, Massamba Sylla and Brian Foy in Senegal in 2008 with equipment for aspirating mosquitoes. Dr. Foy became sick with Zika after returning to his home in Colorado, and most likely transmitted the virus to his wife sexually.

item.title: Opposition Groups in Moldova Unite to Protest New Government
item.description: More than 15,000 people demonstrated on Sunday after a new prime minister, Pavel Filip, was named to lead the country’s third government in a year.
item.dc:creator: KIT GILLET
